05370nam a22007815i 9780691236827DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a9780691236827  a(DE-B1597)612947  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aLC212.42b.O74 2022 7aEDU0150002bisacsh04a378.1/610973223/eng/202110061 aOrfield, Gary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Walls around Opportunity :bThe Failure of Colorblind Policy for Higher Education /cGary Orfield. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b6 b/w illus. 4 tables.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aOur Compelling Interests ;v60 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOpening college gates: the case for race-conscious education policyIn our unequal society, families of color fully share the dream of college but their children often attend schools that do not prepare them, and the higher education system gives the best opportunities to the most privileged. Students of color hope for college but often face a dead end.For many young people, racial inequality puts them at a disadvantage from early childhood. The Walls around Opportunity argues that colorblind policies have made college inaccessible to a large share of students of color, and reveals how policies that acknowledge racial inequalities and set racial equality goals can succeed where colorblindness has failed.Gary Orfield paints a troubling portrait of American higher education, explaining how profound racial gaps imbedded in virtually every stage of our children’s lives pose a major threat to communities of color and the nation. He describes how the l960s and early 1970s was the only period in history to witness sustained efforts at racial equity in higher education, and how the Reagan era ushered in today’s colorblind policies, which ignore the realities of color inequality. Orfield shows how this misguided policy has resegregated public schools, exacerbated inequalities in college preparation, denied needed financial aid to families, and led to huge price increases over decades that have seen little real gain in income for most Americans.Drawing on a wealth of new data and featuring commentaries by Stella Flores and James Anderson, this timely and urgent book shows how colorblind policies serve only to raise the walls of segregation higher, and proposes real solutions that can make higher education available to all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAffirmative action programs in educationzUnited States. 0aEducational equalizationzUnited States. 0aHigher education and statezUnited States. 0aMinority college studentszUnited StatesxSocial conditions. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdmission. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, James D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCantor, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlores, Stella M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Earl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2022 Englishz978311099395008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2022z9783110994186oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022